or, and women, connect their efforts to broader social justice struggles today. A timely, worthwhile read, Organizing While Undocumented gives us a look at inspiring triumphs, as well as the inevitable perils, of political activism in precarious times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aIllegal aliensxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited States. 0aImmigrant youthxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aImmigrant youthxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aImmigrant youthxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aImmigrant youthxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aNoncitizensxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aSocial justicezUnited States. 0aYouth protest movementszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aAsian immigrants.  aAsian undocumented immigration.  aAsian undocumented.  aIdentity Mobilization Model.  aMuslim immigrants and refugees.  ablack undocumented immigrants.  acoming out.  aformerly undocumented activists.  aformerly undocumented immigrant women.  aimmigrant legal status.  aimmigrant rights activists.  aimmigrant rights movement.  aintersectional identities.  amultiracial.  amultisited ethnographic approach.  asocial movement activism.  atransformative social change.  atransgender undocumented immigrants.  aundocuqueer activists.  aundocuqueer.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831107227030 cprintz978147980319440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479803194.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479877812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479877812/original  a978-3-11-072270-3  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EB